Plot
====

Overview
--------
plot/ contains rendering code only.
It reads already-persisted analysis outputs and turns them into canvases,
histograms, and image files. It should not own selection logic, persistence
schema, or systematic evaluation.

The main surfaces are:

  EventListIO      --reads--> event displays and row-wise plots
  DistributionIO   --reads--> cached histogram payloads
  Plotter          --renders-> stacked and unstacked channel views
  EfficiencyPlot   --renders-> denominator / numerator + efficiency overlays

Public surface
--------------
EventDisplay.hh
  EventDisplay plus draw_event_display(...) helpers for detector and semantic
  image views from EventListIO selected trees.

EventListPlotting.hh
  Small helpers for one-off selected-tree histograms and for rebuilding a
  TH1D from one DistributionIO entry.

EfficiencyPlot.hh
  plot_utils::EfficiencyPlot for denominator / passed histograms with a
  right-axis efficiency overlay and optional weighted-event mode.

PlotDescriptors.hh
  Shared plain-data descriptors for plot specifications, per-sample entries,
  options, cuts, and histogram models.

Plotter.hh
  Thin orchestration class for the main stacked and unstacked plot paths.

StackedHist.hh
  Concrete stacked MC + data renderer with optional ratio panel and
  uncertainty band.

UnstackedHist.hh
  Concrete overlay-style renderer for channel-separated views.

PlotChannels.hh
  Central mapping from analysis-channel codes to names, labels, and colours.

PlottingHelper.hh
  Small helper functions used by the renderers to build entries, combine
  selections, and fill TH1D objects.

Rendering notes
---------------
The preferred downstream path is to read EventListIO directly for most plots.
The plotting layer can also consume DistributionIO payloads when a persisted
bin-wise product already exists.

The stack / unstack path assumes the usual EventListIO-derived columns such as
__analysis_channel__ and __w__.

Boundary notes
--------------
plot/ should stay a narrow rendering module:

  persisted rows or bins
      ->
  ROOT histograms / canvases / image files

If code starts deciding physics selections, building caches, or reshaping
persistent schemas, it belongs in ana/, syst/, or io/ instead.
